# Rust style

The authoritative external references are the
[Rust API Guidelines](https://rust-lang.github.io/api-guidelines/) and
[rustfmt](https://rust-lang.github.io/rustfmt/) defaults. Rules below
either match or tighten them.

## Formatting

- **`rustfmt` defaults — no custom `rustfmt.toml`** unless there's a
  specific, recorded reason. Hand-formatting is forbidden.
  Run `cargo fmt --all` (recipe: `just rust-fmt`).
- **Line length:** rustfmt default (100). Don't argue.
- Trailing commas everywhere they're allowed.

## Edition and toolchain

- **Edition 2021 minimum.** Use 2024 if the project was created after
  it stabilised.
- Pin the toolchain explicitly with `rust-toolchain.toml` so CI and
  contributors agree. Use `stable` unless a specific feature requires
  nightly (in which case justify it next to the pin).

## Naming (from the API Guidelines, C-CASE)

- `snake_case` — modules, functions, methods, variables, lifetimes
  (`'a`).
- `UpperCamelCase` — types, traits, type parameters (`T`, `K`, `Item`),
  enum variants.
- `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE` — `const` and `static`.
- Conversion methods: `as_*` (free, no allocation), `to_*` (borrowed →
  owned), `into_*` (consumes self). Don't invent fourth names.
- Getters: no `get_` prefix. `foo.name()`, not `foo.get_name()`. Setter
  is `set_name`.
- Predicates return `bool` and are named with `is_` / `has_` / `can_`.
- Iterator-returning methods: `iter()` (borrow), `iter_mut()` (mut
  borrow), `into_iter()` (consume).

## Documentation

- Public items must have `///` doc comments. Use full sentences, link
  to related items with intra-doc links (`[`Foo`]`).
- **Every public item gets at least one runnable example** in a doc
  test (the API guidelines call this out explicitly). Doc tests are
  examples and tests at once.
- Document panic conditions in a `# Panics` section; document errors
  in `# Errors`; document `unsafe` preconditions in `# Safety`.

```rust
/// Computes the area of a circle.
///
/// # Errors
///
/// Returns [`Error::NegativeRadius`] if `radius` is negative.
///
/// # Examples
///
/// ```
/// # use mycrate::circle_area;
/// assert!((circle_area(1.0).unwrap() - std::f64::consts::PI).abs() < 1e-9);
/// ```
pub fn circle_area(radius: f64) -> Result<f64, Error> { /* … */ }
```

## Imports and modules

- Group imports by source: `std` / external crates / `crate::` / `super`
  / `self`. rustfmt handles this when `group_imports = "StdExternalCrate"`
  is set, but the project uses defaults — manual grouping is fine and
  rustfmt won't undo it.
- Don't `use foo::*` outside of preludes or trait-method-bringing
  patterns. Be explicit.
- Modules are small files; `mod.rs` is allowed but the modern
  convention is `foo.rs` + `foo/`-subdirectory.

## Error handling — the bedrock rule

- **Libraries use `thiserror`.** Define a crate-level error enum with
  `#[derive(thiserror::Error)]`. Each variant is a specific failure
  with a `#[from]` for transparent conversion where it makes sense.
- **Binaries use `anyhow`.** `anyhow::Result<T>` everywhere by default.
  Add `.context("doing X")` at each layer.
- **Never `unwrap()` or `expect("...")` in production code paths.**
  In tests and `main()` where panic is acceptable: fine, but always
  pair `expect` with a useful message.
- Prefer `?` for propagation. Use the `From`/`Into` derive on your
  error types so `?` works seamlessly.
- `panic!` is for unrecoverable invariant violations only. Never panic
  in a library API for ordinary input errors — return a `Result`.

## Lints

- **Clippy must be clean.** `cargo clippy --all-targets --all-features
  -- -D warnings` is the gate. (Recipe: `just rust-lint`.)
- Project lints in `Cargo.toml`:

  ```toml
  [lints.rust]
  unsafe_code = "forbid"   # remove if you legitimately need unsafe
  missing_docs = "warn"

  [lints.clippy]
  pedantic = { level = "warn", priority = -1 }
  unwrap_used = "warn"
  expect_used = "warn"
  panic = "warn"
  todo = "warn"
  unimplemented = "warn"
  ```

  Loosen these per-crate only with a documented reason.

## `unsafe`

- Default to forbidding it (`#![forbid(unsafe_code)]`).
- If you need it: scope to the smallest possible block, write a
  `// SAFETY: ...` comment explaining every invariant the caller must
  uphold, and pair with a sound safe wrapper.

## Loose ends to avoid

- `.clone()` for "just to make it compile". Each clone is a copy —
  either borrow, restructure, or accept the cost knowingly.
- `Box<dyn Trait>` when generics would do. Use `impl Trait` or generics
  for performance-sensitive paths; reserve dyn dispatch for genuine
  heterogeneity.
- `Rc<RefCell<...>>` in `domain/`. If you need interior mutability in
  pure domain logic, you've usually modelled the problem wrong.
- Returning `&str` from a function that allocates — return `String`.
- `String` parameters when `&str` would do. Take the slice; let the
  caller choose ownership.
- `Vec` parameters when `&[T]` would do, same logic.
